WEBVTT

00:00.917 --> 00:01.960
[TV static drones]

00:02.043 --> 00:04.879
[bright tone]

00:04.963 --> 00:07.799
[spirited orchestral music]

00:07.882 --> 00:15.015
♪ ♪

01:40.265 --> 01:43.395
[cheerful music]

01:43.436 --> 01:50.402
♪ ♪

01:51.485 --> 01:53.780
- Mr. Russell is expecting me.

01:53.863 --> 01:57.533
- If you'll come this way, sir,
Mr. Russell is in the library.

02:00.662 --> 02:02.372
Mr. Tate.

02:05.417 --> 02:08.044
- I thought it was your father
I was here to see.

02:08.086 --> 02:10.338
- I hope I'm not
a disappointment.

02:12.924 --> 02:15.385
- But there is to be
a reception at their home,

02:15.427 --> 02:17.262
which the president
will attend,

02:17.303 --> 02:19.055
and Mrs. Roebling
will be the hostess.

02:19.097 --> 02:22.058
Isn't that enough?
- No, not nearly.

02:22.100 --> 02:24.185
Mrs. Roebling has been
managing construction

02:24.269 --> 02:25.853
of the eighth wonder
of the world.

02:25.895 --> 02:27.439
- She took orders
from her husband,

02:27.480 --> 02:29.524
and she will be thanked for it
by the mayor at the opening.

02:29.607 --> 02:31.568
- Mr. Roebling has been
convalescing for years.

02:31.609 --> 02:33.695
He couldn't have given
directions every day,

02:33.778 --> 02:35.280
even if he wanted to.

02:35.321 --> 02:38.116
- To reveal now
that the Brooklyn Bridge

02:38.199 --> 02:39.909
is largely the work of a woman

02:39.951 --> 02:42.287
would make men afraid
to cross it.

02:42.328 --> 02:44.539
- [scoffs]
She told me you'd say that.

02:44.622 --> 02:46.499
- I cannot endanger
the whole event

02:46.583 --> 02:48.793
out of pity for Mrs. Roebling.

02:51.296 --> 02:52.964
- That's disappointing to hear.

02:53.048 --> 02:59.929
♪ ♪

03:04.142 --> 03:05.643
- Well?

03:05.685 --> 03:07.062
- The men are back to work,
and the mills

03:07.145 --> 03:08.730
are running at full production.

03:08.813 --> 03:10.315
- You sound surprised.

03:10.357 --> 03:12.275
- I'm not at all surprised,
given the offer you made.

03:12.317 --> 03:15.195
More safeguards, medical care,
children's park.

03:15.278 --> 03:16.988
It was a list
from a fairy tale.

03:17.030 --> 03:18.448
- Don't forget the pay raise.

03:18.490 --> 03:20.575
- You joke, but you've broken
your word to the others.

03:20.658 --> 03:23.119
- I have only done what they
will all do sooner or later.

03:23.161 --> 03:25.329
- You mean give in?
- Not quite.

03:25.372 --> 03:28.500
I've offered a modest raise
on a six-month contract

03:28.541 --> 03:30.585
to the tradesmen,
and only to the tradesmen.

03:30.669 --> 03:32.003
- Exactly.

03:32.087 --> 03:33.672
- It will split the union
down the middle.

03:33.713 --> 03:36.925
And when it does,
we will reassert our control.

03:37.008 --> 03:40.512
- So you've tricked them?
- I prefer to call it tactics.

03:40.553 --> 03:42.514
By the time
the contract lapses,

03:42.597 --> 03:45.141
the craftsmen and the laborers
will hate each other,

03:45.225 --> 03:47.185
and everyone will hate
the Catholic immigrants

03:47.268 --> 03:48.269
and the Jews.

03:48.353 --> 03:50.355
In the meantime,

03:50.397 --> 03:51.856
get Henderson back to New York.

03:51.940 --> 03:54.442
We'll have a photograph taken
of my shaking his hand.

03:54.526 --> 03:56.986
- To celebrate your victory.
- Certainly not.

03:57.070 --> 04:00.198
For now, he must
look like the winner.

04:00.240 --> 04:02.992
♪ ♪

04:03.034 --> 04:05.578
- I'll have one more, please.
They're quite tasty.

04:05.662 --> 04:07.038
- Are you all right,
Miss Armstrong?

04:07.080 --> 04:08.206
- Yes, why?

04:08.289 --> 04:09.666
- Well, you said
something nice.

04:09.708 --> 04:11.376
- I can't compliment
Mrs. Bauer's cooking?

04:11.459 --> 04:13.753
- Oh, you can,
but it's just so unlike you.

04:13.837 --> 04:15.755
- I give praise
when it is deserved.

04:15.839 --> 04:17.716
- Oh, John.
- Yes, Mr. Bannister?

04:17.757 --> 04:19.718
- I have a friend
coming here this afternoon,

04:19.759 --> 04:20.677
a Mr. Schubert.

04:20.719 --> 04:22.387
I wrote to him
about your predicament,

04:22.429 --> 04:24.597
and he's agreed to meet you
to see if there's anything

04:24.681 --> 04:26.307
to be done about your patent.

04:26.391 --> 04:28.393
- But they turned me down.
Isn't that the end of it?

04:28.476 --> 04:30.103
- Well, Mr. Schubert will know.

04:30.186 --> 04:31.354
He's the secretary

04:31.396 --> 04:33.732
of the Uhrmacher Verein
der Stadt New York.

04:33.815 --> 04:36.526
- Do you speak German now?
- What does it mean?

04:36.568 --> 04:39.320
- The Watchmakers' Association
of the City of New York.

04:39.404 --> 04:41.489
It was founded
by some German clockmakers

04:41.573 --> 04:42.907
at the end of the war,

04:42.949 --> 04:45.284
and now it wields
considerable influence.

04:45.368 --> 04:47.078
- Why would he bother with me?

04:47.162 --> 04:49.706
- As a favor to me.
- How exciting.

04:49.748 --> 04:52.207
- Shouldn't you
take the silver up?

04:52.250 --> 04:53.710
- Right away.

04:53.752 --> 04:55.587
- [chuckles]

04:57.464 --> 05:00.175
- You sure you feel
up to going?

05:00.258 --> 05:02.927
- I do.
It's Marian's engagement.

05:02.969 --> 05:06.931
- She'll understand.
I can represent us both.

05:06.973 --> 05:09.726
There's no need
to put yourself through it.

05:09.768 --> 05:13.438
- I intend to keep living
my life while I can.

05:13.521 --> 05:16.524
- I just worry
that if you go over there,

05:16.608 --> 05:20.195
Agnes will try to persuade us
again to move in with her.

05:20.278 --> 05:22.447
- I'd rather we stay here.

05:22.530 --> 05:24.657
- I won't leave your side.

05:24.741 --> 05:28.745
You may tire of me,
but I'm not going anywhere.

05:28.787 --> 05:32.665
- I will never grow weary
of you, Mrs. Forte.

05:36.002 --> 05:37.295
- [sighs]

05:37.379 --> 05:38.630
- What do you think
of this one?

05:38.672 --> 05:41.633
- It's pretty.
They're all pretty.

05:44.094 --> 05:48.306
- It just feels wrong,
when Uncle Luke is so ill.

05:48.348 --> 05:50.308
- Mrs. Forte won't grudge it.

05:50.350 --> 05:51.810
She's glad you're engaged.

05:51.893 --> 05:55.146
They wouldn't come
to the luncheon otherwise.

05:55.230 --> 05:58.149
- Was I right to accept him?

05:58.191 --> 06:00.652
- Well, only you
can answer that.

06:00.735 --> 06:04.406
But he seems a nice man.
- He is nice.

06:04.489 --> 06:08.618
And kind, and a good father,
and all of those things.

06:08.660 --> 06:11.121
- Are you trying
to persuade yourself?

06:13.832 --> 06:15.500
- Not at all.

06:15.542 --> 06:16.835
I am persuaded.

06:16.918 --> 06:19.129
- Then enjoy
your luncheon in peace.

06:19.170 --> 06:22.507
- [laughs]
Yes, I will.

06:22.590 --> 06:26.011
- I thought you'd be overjoyed.

06:26.052 --> 06:27.595
- To be honest, I'm stunned.

06:27.679 --> 06:30.265
- Well, I've pulled
a lot of strings,

06:30.348 --> 06:32.433
and I'm afraid
I've pushed others aside

06:32.517 --> 06:34.352
to get you to the top
of the list.

06:34.436 --> 06:36.021
- For which I'm grateful,
of course.

06:36.062 --> 06:39.941
- Wasn't a box at the Academy
what you've always wanted?

06:40.025 --> 06:41.192
- It was.

06:41.234 --> 06:42.736
- And now you have it.

06:42.819 --> 06:47.198
So can we put this Metropolitan
business to rest?

06:47.282 --> 06:49.701
- I must discuss it
with Mr. Russell.

06:49.743 --> 06:52.537
- I think he'll be
very pleased for you.

06:56.624 --> 06:58.626
I should be on my way.

06:58.710 --> 07:00.378
There's so much
to do for the opening

07:00.462 --> 07:01.546
of the Brooklyn Bridge.

07:01.629 --> 07:03.840
- Mr. Russell is one
of the trustees.

07:03.882 --> 07:05.675
We're watching
the opening itself,

07:05.717 --> 07:07.010
and then we'll go
to a reception

07:07.093 --> 07:08.219
that Mrs. Roebling is giving.

07:08.303 --> 07:10.555
- Yes, I know.
I'm helping her with it.

07:10.597 --> 07:13.600
She's never entertained
for a president before.

07:13.683 --> 07:16.227
- Quite a responsibility.
- I suppose.

07:16.269 --> 07:18.563
President Arthur is a nice man,

07:18.646 --> 07:21.316
and I believe
he was successful as a lawyer.

07:21.358 --> 07:24.903
But his origins
are not exactly inspiring.

07:24.986 --> 07:26.237
- You know him then?

07:26.321 --> 07:28.406
- We meet in the way of things.

07:28.448 --> 07:30.158
I'll present you, if you like.

07:30.241 --> 07:32.744
- I should be honored.
- That's settled, then.

07:32.827 --> 07:34.454
[chuckles]

07:35.622 --> 07:37.040
Will I be seeing you

07:37.082 --> 07:39.125
at Mrs. Fane's
charity committee this week?

07:39.209 --> 07:40.543
- You will.

07:40.585 --> 07:41.836
- Might you have spoken
to Mr. Russell

07:41.920 --> 07:43.797
about the Academy box by then?

07:43.880 --> 07:46.508
- I should think so.
- Good.

07:46.591 --> 07:49.094
I'm sure he'll be delighted,
my dear.

07:49.135 --> 07:52.931
♪ ♪

07:52.972 --> 07:55.266
- Your carriage
is ready, ma'am.

08:00.146 --> 08:01.481
- Excuse me, everyone.

08:01.564 --> 08:03.942
I want to thank
you all for coming,

08:04.025 --> 08:08.446
and praise my daughter
and her editor, Mr. Fortune,

08:08.488 --> 08:10.115
for taking up the cause.

08:10.198 --> 08:11.908
Mr. Fortune.
- Yes.

08:11.950 --> 08:14.369
Now, these attempts
to denigrate our teachers

08:14.452 --> 08:16.246
and close our schools
will be fought.

08:16.287 --> 08:18.164
"The Globe"
will publish articles

08:18.248 --> 08:19.957
stressing our teachers' merits.

08:20.000 --> 08:22.168
- Would that be enough
to keep the schools open?

08:22.252 --> 08:23.795
- Not that alone.

08:23.878 --> 08:25.839
I've spoken
to some other educators,

08:25.922 --> 08:28.550
white educators,
and the fact is,

08:28.633 --> 08:30.844
we need to increase
the number of pupils.

08:30.927 --> 08:33.972
Specifically, we need
to enroll white students

08:34.054 --> 08:36.433
in our schools
for the board to even care.

08:36.474 --> 08:38.143
- We don't want
integrated schools.

08:38.183 --> 08:40.227
- But if it's the only way
to keep them open,

08:40.311 --> 08:41.604
do we have a choice?

08:41.645 --> 08:44.649
- No.
Mrs. Garnet is right.

08:44.691 --> 08:47.694
I work with these people
every day in my drugstores.

08:47.777 --> 08:50.488
The only reason they ever
trusted me in the first place

08:50.530 --> 08:52.699
is because a white pharmacist
told them to.

08:52.782 --> 08:54.576
- Well, what does that have
to do with the schools?

08:54.617 --> 08:57.037
- Well, "The Globe" can
praise our colored teachers

08:57.120 --> 08:59.289
to the heavens,
but none of those white parents

08:59.372 --> 09:01.166
will send their children
to our schools

09:01.207 --> 09:04.502
unless they are persuaded
by someone white.

09:04.586 --> 09:06.671
And we may have to recruit
some white teachers too.

09:06.713 --> 09:08.173
- Oh.
- I don't like that.

09:08.214 --> 09:10.675
- I don't know how we're
going to manage that.

09:10.717 --> 09:13.178
- I may have an idea.

09:14.804 --> 09:20.352
- So, Marian and Dashiell, I
can only wish you the happiness

09:20.393 --> 09:22.645
that your Aunt Ada
has brought me.

09:22.687 --> 09:24.773
- Here, here.
- Cheers.

09:26.399 --> 09:29.361
- Oscar, before I forget,
Mrs. Astor has invited you

09:29.444 --> 09:31.446
to the Academy
for the opening night.

09:31.529 --> 09:33.281
- I don't know if I'm free.

09:33.323 --> 09:34.908
- You're free,
and you're coming.

09:34.991 --> 09:38.161
And now we should
begin wedding plans.

09:38.244 --> 09:39.621
- We've not been long engaged.

09:39.704 --> 09:41.164
- And I'd like
to see you married

09:41.247 --> 09:42.582
as soon as we can arrange it.

09:42.665 --> 09:43.958
We should get
the dress started.

09:44.042 --> 09:45.335
That will take the time.
- Oh, yes.

09:45.377 --> 09:47.003
- But I--
- Don't try to argue.

09:47.045 --> 09:49.464
- I should tell you
that Frances is determined

09:49.547 --> 09:51.049
to be a part
of the preparations.

09:51.091 --> 09:53.259
- [laughs]
I'm to allow a 14-year-old girl

09:53.343 --> 09:54.552
to plan Marian's wedding?

09:54.594 --> 09:56.888
- I think Frances
would insist on it.

09:56.971 --> 09:58.515
[laughter]

09:58.556 --> 09:59.891
- Mr. Montgomery--

09:59.974 --> 10:01.559
- Are you still being
good to Miss Beaton?

10:01.601 --> 10:02.894
Please say yes.

10:02.977 --> 10:04.896
- I'm sad you think
so little of me.

10:04.979 --> 10:06.648
- I thought she might be here.

10:06.731 --> 10:08.066
- She's in Newport
for a few days.

10:08.108 --> 10:09.984
She has an aunt there
who's been ill.

10:10.068 --> 10:11.778
But you have nothing
to worry about.

10:11.861 --> 10:13.863
We're going to the Brooklyn
Bridge festivities.

10:13.905 --> 10:15.907
And I mean to propose,

10:15.990 --> 10:18.576
if that will put
your mind at rest.

10:18.618 --> 10:20.245
- Well, if that's true,
I'm relieved.

10:20.328 --> 10:22.497
[laughs]
And so glad.

10:22.580 --> 10:24.207
[indistinct chatter]

10:24.249 --> 10:28.420
- Oscar, you need to escort
the bride down the aisle.

10:28.461 --> 10:29.921
- I'd be delighted.

10:29.963 --> 10:31.423
- Aurora and I are hoping
you will allow us

10:31.464 --> 10:32.507
to give the wedding reception.

10:32.590 --> 10:34.551
- Oh!
- It would be our pleasure.

10:34.592 --> 10:36.928
- Oh, how very kind.
Thank you.

10:36.970 --> 10:40.598
- And the service will be
at St. Thomas, of course.

10:40.640 --> 10:43.435
- It will be an honor
to marry you.

10:43.518 --> 10:48.481
♪ ♪

10:48.565 --> 10:50.775
- Oh, Mr. Fortune.
- Oh, hello.

10:50.817 --> 10:54.446
- We are so pleased we could
finally meet you in person

10:54.487 --> 10:56.281
and thank you
for the opportunity

10:56.322 --> 10:57.449
you've given to Peggy.

10:57.490 --> 10:58.700
- Of course,
you should be so proud

10:58.783 --> 11:00.285
of her accomplishments
at "The Globe."

11:00.326 --> 11:01.619
- We are.

11:01.661 --> 11:02.871
- She helped me immensely
in Tuskegee.

11:02.954 --> 11:04.706
- Oh, I read the article.

11:04.789 --> 11:08.543
I noticed that only
you two were credited.

11:08.626 --> 11:10.754
How many others went with you?

11:10.795 --> 11:12.797
- Mother, we shouldn't
take up any more

11:12.881 --> 11:14.507
of Mr. Fortune's time.

11:14.591 --> 11:16.134
Thank you for coming.

11:16.176 --> 11:19.346
- I'll see you all tomorrow?
- Oh, you will.

11:21.056 --> 11:24.017
- You were enthusiastic today.
What was that about?

11:24.100 --> 11:26.895
- Well, it's a good cause,
a righteous cause.

11:26.978 --> 11:28.730
And I'm supporting my wife.

11:28.813 --> 11:32.108
- Oh, my word.
Am I hearing right?

11:32.150 --> 11:34.486
Peggy, can we coax you
to come back with us,

11:34.527 --> 11:36.071
or do you have
to take the ferry?

11:36.154 --> 11:37.697
- I can stay.

11:37.781 --> 11:39.949
- By this time next week,
Peggy will be able

11:39.991 --> 11:43.036
to cross the Brooklyn Bridge
to visit us in no time.

11:43.119 --> 11:45.497
- You have to come back
for the opening.

11:45.538 --> 11:48.375
The Wyatts are throwing a party
on their rooftop to watch it.

11:48.458 --> 11:51.461
- I'll see, Mother.
- No, no, no, you'll come.

11:53.004 --> 11:55.256
- So it was born of necessity?

11:55.340 --> 11:56.883
- That's it.
- Hm.

11:56.966 --> 11:59.511
- I figured the problem
was with the escape wheel.

11:59.552 --> 12:01.346
- The escapement.

12:01.429 --> 12:02.889
- Sure.

12:02.972 --> 12:04.849
It seemed like
the old oil was congealing

12:04.933 --> 12:06.184
and slowing it down.

12:06.267 --> 12:08.186
- Yes, I have
suspected this before.

12:08.269 --> 12:10.897
- So I constructed
a new kind of wheel

12:10.980 --> 12:13.566
that runs without oil.

12:13.650 --> 12:15.527
- How ingenious.

12:15.610 --> 12:18.363
And it works?
- Every time.

12:19.698 --> 12:22.867
- Well, Mr. Trotter,
I will see what I can do

12:22.909 --> 12:24.703
in terms of your membership.

12:24.744 --> 12:26.371
- My membership, sir?

12:26.413 --> 12:28.998
- Of the Uhrmacher Verein
der Stadt New York.

12:29.040 --> 12:30.875
You clearly know
more about clocks

12:30.917 --> 12:33.128
than many of our members.

12:35.213 --> 12:36.715
- [chuckles]

12:36.798 --> 12:38.383
[bell rings]

12:38.466 --> 12:40.343
- Oh!

12:41.761 --> 12:43.513
- Ah, Bannister.
- Yes, ma'am.

12:43.555 --> 12:45.557
- Mr. and Mrs. Forte
are leaving.

12:45.598 --> 12:47.392
- I must go as well.

12:47.475 --> 12:52.022
I hadn't realized the time,
and Frances is waiting.

12:52.063 --> 12:53.732
- Well, please tell--oh!
- [groans]

12:53.773 --> 12:55.358
- Oh, Luke!

12:55.442 --> 12:56.735
My darling, are you all right?

12:56.818 --> 12:58.570
- That settles it.
You're staying here.

12:58.653 --> 13:00.113
Bannister, will you fetch John?

13:00.196 --> 13:02.907
We should get Mr. Forte into
bed and send for Dr. Lewis.

13:02.949 --> 13:04.951
- Right away.
- [groans]

13:05.035 --> 13:07.120
- I'll have John
fetch the doctor.

13:26.514 --> 13:28.683
- What was that for?

13:28.767 --> 13:30.310
- I can't stop thinking
about Pittsburgh

13:30.393 --> 13:33.146
and what could have happened
if they started firing.

13:34.397 --> 13:37.442
- Well, they didn't.

13:37.525 --> 13:39.527
- Are things under control now?

13:39.569 --> 13:42.113
- I think they will be.
- [sighs]

13:43.156 --> 13:45.784
I thought the opera war
was under control too.

13:45.825 --> 13:47.535
But Mrs. Astor
has made me an offer,

13:47.619 --> 13:48.953
and now I don't
know what to do.

13:48.995 --> 13:50.663
- What sort of offer?

13:50.747 --> 13:54.084
- A box
at the Academy of Music.

13:54.125 --> 13:56.252
- And?
- I must consider it, George.

13:56.294 --> 13:57.962
She obviously went
through a lot of trouble

13:58.004 --> 13:59.130
to get it for us.

13:59.214 --> 14:02.300
- Of course she did.
To buy you off.

14:02.342 --> 14:04.094
- So you think
I should turn it down?

14:04.135 --> 14:07.305
- Your argument for a new
opera house holds good.

14:07.347 --> 14:09.349
The Academy is too small,
too unambitious.

14:09.432 --> 14:13.311
And it excludes the people
who are making the city great.

14:13.353 --> 14:15.730
Why would you give up
your goal now?

14:15.772 --> 14:19.818
- My goal was always
a box at the Academy.

14:19.859 --> 14:23.530
- At the Met,
you'll be a founding member,

14:23.613 --> 14:25.824
and you can reign supreme.

14:25.865 --> 14:28.576
You don't need to be
in Mrs. Astor's shadow.

14:28.660 --> 14:30.787
- You make a good case.

14:30.829 --> 14:33.790
- It's your case.
I'm just repeating it.

14:33.832 --> 14:37.585
[soft music]

14:37.669 --> 14:39.838
- I feel a bit better today.

14:39.921 --> 14:41.506
- That's good, isn't it?

14:41.548 --> 14:44.801
- And I had a little breakfast.
- Good.

14:44.843 --> 14:47.679
Send for me if things change.
- Mm.

14:53.351 --> 14:54.936
[door clicks]

14:55.020 --> 14:58.023
- Dr. Lewis,
may I take him home?

14:58.106 --> 15:00.525
He looks better,
and he has his appetite back.

15:00.567 --> 15:02.944
- I would not advise it.
- What does that mean?

15:03.028 --> 15:05.321
- I'm afraid at this stage,
it's out of my hands.

15:05.363 --> 15:08.074
We can only pray.

15:08.158 --> 15:11.953
- That's a clever way
to shirk your responsibility.

15:13.580 --> 15:15.874
- I will check on him again.

15:15.915 --> 15:18.293
- Thank you, Dr. Lewis.

15:20.545 --> 15:23.673
- Ada, you look ragged.

15:23.715 --> 15:25.800
- I don't care.
- Go and lie down.

15:25.884 --> 15:28.053
I'll watch over him.
- No.

15:28.136 --> 15:31.431
My place is here.
- Ada, go and lie down.

15:31.514 --> 15:33.808
I can sit with Luke.

15:33.892 --> 15:36.061
Go.

15:38.229 --> 15:40.106
[sighs]

15:40.190 --> 15:43.234
- Mrs. Garnet has
an excellent curriculum

15:43.276 --> 15:45.362
and committed teachers.

15:45.403 --> 15:47.906
Anyone would be lucky
to teach at

15:47.947 --> 15:50.909
or attend one of these schools.

15:50.992 --> 15:53.745
With your help,
we can make the board realize

15:53.828 --> 15:56.289
they have to keep them open.

15:56.373 --> 15:58.249
- Thank you, Miss Brook,
for coming out today

15:58.290 --> 16:00.377
and supporting our cause.

16:00.418 --> 16:03.421
If there are teachers who have
not registered their interest,

16:03.505 --> 16:06.508
please move to the back of
the room where you can do so.

16:06.591 --> 16:09.803
[indistinct chatter]

16:09.886 --> 16:11.179
- You did well.

16:11.262 --> 16:13.306
- Do you think so?
- Mm-hmm.

16:13.390 --> 16:15.600
- I just hope enough
people sign up.

16:15.684 --> 16:16.851
- Excuse me, ladies.

16:16.935 --> 16:18.728
Mr. Hastings
is another pharmacist.

16:18.770 --> 16:20.522
- And a member
of the school board.

16:20.605 --> 16:23.191
I wanted you to meet a friend
of mine, Mr. Patrick Ryan.

16:23.274 --> 16:25.652
He is a teacher.
- Where do you teach?

16:25.735 --> 16:27.404
- Nowhere just now.

16:27.445 --> 16:29.280
Irish teachers
and students face

16:29.322 --> 16:31.032
our own set of prejudices.

16:31.116 --> 16:33.451
- Would you consider
coming to work with me?

16:33.535 --> 16:36.121
- I've been impressed
this afternoon by Miss Brook.

16:36.204 --> 16:37.831
I've been looking
for work for some time,

16:37.914 --> 16:39.124
and I'd like to join you.

16:39.165 --> 16:41.376
Also there
are plenty of others,

16:41.459 --> 16:44.170
and I think I can convince some
of them to follow me.

16:44.254 --> 16:47.173
- I hope so because one
white teacher won't be enough.

16:47.257 --> 16:49.426
- That's one more
than we had yesterday.

16:49.467 --> 16:51.302
- Once I bring
the other white teachers,

16:51.344 --> 16:53.179
the white pupils will come.

16:53.263 --> 16:55.974
- Don't you see?
This may be our way forward.

16:56.016 --> 16:58.435
We'll have the mix
of children that we need.

16:58.476 --> 17:01.271
I'm really starting
to think we may win.

17:01.312 --> 17:03.314
God bless you, Mr. Ryan.

17:03.356 --> 17:08.819
♪ ♪

17:08.862 --> 17:10.195
- That should do it.

17:10.280 --> 17:12.156
- Thank you, gentlemen.
Right this way.

17:12.240 --> 17:15.367
- Press is declaring this
a victory for labor.

17:15.452 --> 17:18.163
They praise your spirit
of moderate compromise.

17:18.204 --> 17:19.955
- Is that so?
- Mm-hmm.

17:19.998 --> 17:21.040
- Please.

17:21.124 --> 17:24.127
- But we both know better,
Mr. Russell.

17:24.210 --> 17:27.172
- The tradesmen will enjoy
a 10% increase for six months.

17:27.213 --> 17:28.590
What's wrong with that?

17:28.673 --> 17:30.842
- You know it'll set
the laborers against them.

17:30.925 --> 17:32.802
And almost all
our skilled craftsmen

17:32.844 --> 17:34.346
are American born and bred.

17:34.429 --> 17:36.514
Your terms leave
the immigrants on the outside.

17:36.556 --> 17:39.225
- They'll benefit too.
The workplace will be safer.

17:39.309 --> 17:40.769
Their health
will be in good hands.

17:40.852 --> 17:42.979
They'll even have a park
where their children can play.

17:43.063 --> 17:45.774
- But you don't intend
to recognize the union.

17:45.857 --> 17:47.359
- Not yet.

17:47.442 --> 17:50.153
- Carriage is here,
Mr. Henderson.

17:50.195 --> 17:53.365
- Shall I tell you why
I accepted the terms?

17:53.448 --> 17:55.492
Because you didn't allow them
to fire on the men

17:55.575 --> 17:57.202
when you could have.

17:58.370 --> 18:00.705
- You've made the right
decision, Mr. Henderson.

18:00.747 --> 18:03.917
- All I want is for the workers
to have decent lives.

18:04.000 --> 18:06.294
- And you've managed that.

18:13.051 --> 18:14.719
- He knows your plan
is to divide them.

18:14.803 --> 18:16.012
- Of course he does.

18:16.054 --> 18:17.722
But it won't matter
in six months.

18:17.764 --> 18:20.475
- At which point
you'll reduce the payments.

18:20.558 --> 18:21.976
- Indeed.

18:22.060 --> 18:23.520
But I hope
you noticed something.

18:23.561 --> 18:24.979
You thought
we'd lost when I ordered

18:25.063 --> 18:26.314
the militia to stand down.

18:26.398 --> 18:28.358
- It seemed weak to me,
I confess it.

18:28.400 --> 18:31.236
- They opened fire
in the railway strikes of '77,

18:31.277 --> 18:34.280
and all that did was garner
sympathy for the strikers.

18:34.364 --> 18:36.574
Anyway, you heard him.

18:36.616 --> 18:38.243
My moment
of tenderness turns out

18:38.284 --> 18:39.869
to have been my trump card.

18:39.911 --> 18:43.790
♪ ♪

18:43.873 --> 18:45.375
- Hyah!

18:45.417 --> 18:47.085
Hyah!

18:47.127 --> 18:48.753
[horse whinnies]

18:48.795 --> 18:51.673
[indistinct chatter]

18:51.756 --> 18:53.758
♪ ♪

18:53.842 --> 18:55.885
- Can I help you, ma'am?

18:55.927 --> 19:00.432
- Is Mr. Watson here?

19:03.268 --> 19:04.936
- Yes.
- Straight away.

19:05.020 --> 19:07.105
- Whoa!

19:07.147 --> 19:13.069
♪ ♪

19:13.111 --> 19:15.405
- Mr. Watson?

19:17.157 --> 19:19.951
- Flora.
What are you doing here?

19:20.035 --> 19:22.203
I--

19:24.664 --> 19:26.624
come this way.

19:33.048 --> 19:34.799
Why are you here?

19:34.883 --> 19:37.427
Have you come to order me
to leave for California?

19:37.469 --> 19:39.471
- No.

19:39.512 --> 19:41.681
- Do you no longer
want me to go?

19:41.765 --> 19:43.391
- I never did.

19:43.475 --> 19:45.018
You were supposed to have gone

19:45.101 --> 19:48.104
before I knew anything
about it.

19:48.146 --> 19:50.982
My husband thought
he was protecting me,

19:51.024 --> 19:52.484
but he was wrong.

19:52.567 --> 19:55.987
And then I found
your letters to him.

19:56.071 --> 19:58.114
[whimpers]
- Shh.

19:58.156 --> 19:59.824
No.

20:01.993 --> 20:04.496
Everything's going to be fine.

20:09.167 --> 20:11.878
Just tell me,
what do you want me to do?

20:11.961 --> 20:14.756
Whatever it is, I will do it.

20:14.839 --> 20:16.800
- I want you to stay.

20:16.841 --> 20:18.259
Here in New York.

20:18.343 --> 20:21.471
You will have an apartment
with whatever you need,

20:21.513 --> 20:25.809
and you'll be a retired banker
called Collyer.

20:25.850 --> 20:29.979
Which is exactly who you are,
no word of a lie.

20:32.107 --> 20:36.361
- I suppose I must
relinquish my job.

20:37.737 --> 20:41.533
I hope I may see you
and the children sometimes.

20:41.574 --> 20:43.410
- Yes.

20:43.493 --> 20:46.371
And you'll meet our friends
and be in our world

20:46.413 --> 20:48.248
as my father.

20:48.331 --> 20:52.669
♪ ♪

20:52.711 --> 20:56.923
I'll write tomorrow
with a plan.

20:57.007 --> 20:58.883
- [clears throat]

21:00.301 --> 21:03.972
- We'll be all right,
you and me.

21:20.363 --> 21:23.408
- [breathes deeply]

21:24.451 --> 21:25.785
- What are we to make of that?

21:25.869 --> 21:29.330
Did Mrs. McNeil bring
good news or bad?

21:29.414 --> 21:31.583
- The best.

21:32.709 --> 21:34.627
The very best.

21:34.711 --> 21:37.088
- I'm glad.

21:37.172 --> 21:40.216
- It seems I'm
to have a life after all.

21:40.258 --> 21:46.097
♪ ♪

21:46.139 --> 21:49.100
- [groaning]

21:52.979 --> 21:55.273
Where's Ada?

21:55.357 --> 21:58.193
- I hope she's sleeping.

21:58.276 --> 22:00.153
- [grunts]

22:00.236 --> 22:04.199
You're right.
I hope so too.

22:04.282 --> 22:06.951
- I'm glad to have
a moment alone with you.

22:07.035 --> 22:11.164
- It gives me a chance to
thank you for your restraint.

22:11.247 --> 22:12.749
I know you never
wanted the marriage,

22:12.791 --> 22:15.835
and now you've
been proved right.

22:15.919 --> 22:18.296
I was selfish
to take her on at my age.

22:18.338 --> 22:19.756
- No.

22:19.798 --> 22:21.466
You have given my sister
a taste of the kind

22:21.549 --> 22:24.469
of happiness
she had never known.

22:24.552 --> 22:26.346
I see that quite clearly.

22:26.429 --> 22:28.515
- Only to desert her now,

22:28.598 --> 22:31.351
when she's hardly got used
to the sensation.

22:31.434 --> 22:33.687
- It has been too brief,
certainly.

22:33.770 --> 22:36.231
But for the rest
of her time on Earth,

22:36.272 --> 22:40.485
she has only to think
of you to feel warm,

22:40.568 --> 22:44.614
and cherished,
and deeply loved.

22:44.656 --> 22:47.075
You have changed her life.

22:48.535 --> 22:54.124
- That is generous
of you, Agnes.

22:54.165 --> 22:56.835
I know how generous.

22:56.876 --> 22:58.920
- It is the truth.

23:00.505 --> 23:04.426
- Can I ask you
to help Ada when I'm gone?

23:04.509 --> 23:06.511
- Well,
of course I'll help her.

23:06.553 --> 23:08.847
She's my little sister.

23:11.099 --> 23:15.103
Now go back to sleep,

23:15.186 --> 23:16.938
or you'll get me in trouble.

23:17.022 --> 23:18.898
- [chuckles]

23:18.982 --> 23:23.862
♪ ♪

23:23.945 --> 23:26.865
[indistinct chatter]

23:29.701 --> 23:31.703
- Mr. Russell!
- Papers!

23:31.786 --> 23:34.956
Sir, would you like a paper?
- What's that?

23:34.998 --> 23:37.250
- I was just saying hello.

23:37.334 --> 23:39.961
- Hello to you, Mr. Van Rhijn.

23:42.547 --> 23:44.674
- I don't want things
to be awkward between us.

23:44.716 --> 23:46.718
- I assume
you're referring to Gladys.

23:46.760 --> 23:51.056
- Yes, and the matter
with the railway.

23:51.139 --> 23:52.557
- I don't follow you.

23:52.640 --> 23:54.893
- As it turns out,
I'm a substantial shareholder

23:54.934 --> 23:57.062
in the Casterbridge
Pacific company.

23:57.145 --> 23:58.646
- Who?

23:58.730 --> 24:00.398
- The company that bid
against you for the Chicago

24:00.482 --> 24:02.025
and Atlantic line.

24:02.067 --> 24:05.195
- Well, you're right
that we bought the railroad,

24:05.236 --> 24:07.572
though it hasn't
been announced yet.

24:07.614 --> 24:10.575
But I've never heard
of the Casterbridge Pacific.

24:10.658 --> 24:14.204
- I don't understand.
Might you be mistaken?

24:14.245 --> 24:16.873
- I make it my business
to know every major player

24:16.915 --> 24:18.458
in my industry.

24:18.541 --> 24:20.251
If I've not heard of them,

24:20.293 --> 24:22.420
they cannot be
of any consequence.

24:22.504 --> 24:25.006
Good day to you, Mr. Van Rhijn.

24:25.090 --> 24:27.884
♪ ♪

24:27.926 --> 24:29.886
- Congratulations, Miss Scott.
- [laughs]

24:29.928 --> 24:32.097
Remember,
it's only the first step.

24:32.180 --> 24:33.682
- Now, that's true.

24:33.765 --> 24:36.768
It's a shame most of the new
white pupils are Irish.

24:36.810 --> 24:38.520
- That doesn't sound like you.

24:38.561 --> 24:40.605
- Yeah, I'm just not sure
the board think much better

24:40.647 --> 24:42.857
of the Irish than they do
of the colored children.

24:42.941 --> 24:46.611
- In this bright
new democracy of America.

24:48.530 --> 24:50.323
Let me write
an article about it.

24:50.407 --> 24:53.493
Let me shame the board
into making the right decision.

24:53.576 --> 24:56.496
- Fighting talk.
That's what I like to hear.

24:56.579 --> 25:00.125
Let's mark your resolution
with a toast.

25:01.668 --> 25:03.878
- [laughing]
All right.

25:03.920 --> 25:05.964
[clears throat]

25:06.006 --> 25:08.258
- To the survival
of the schools.

25:08.299 --> 25:09.634
- Enough.

25:09.718 --> 25:12.804
- And to the new
integrated students.

25:12.887 --> 25:15.765
- And down
with the Board of Education.

25:15.807 --> 25:18.143
- Mm.
- Richard, I'm taking off.

25:18.226 --> 25:20.645
- See you later.

25:20.687 --> 25:23.273
- Whew.
[laughs]

25:26.026 --> 25:28.653
- [chuckles]

25:28.695 --> 25:30.321
- I should get going.

25:30.363 --> 25:31.614
- Where?

25:31.656 --> 25:33.241
- I'm staying overnight
in Brooklyn.

25:33.324 --> 25:35.618
There's a rooftop party
for the bridge fireworks.

25:35.660 --> 25:38.038
- Ah.
It's a big moment for our city.

25:38.121 --> 25:40.415
- My father even
decorated his storefront,

25:40.498 --> 25:42.042
which he never does.

25:42.125 --> 25:45.712
- I'm having Stephens cover
the bridge story for us.

25:45.795 --> 25:47.339
Let me go down with you
to hail a cab.

25:47.380 --> 25:49.090
- Oh, no need.

25:49.174 --> 25:50.300
both: Oh.

25:50.342 --> 25:52.344
- Excuse me.

25:52.427 --> 25:59.559
♪ ♪

26:00.602 --> 26:02.103
Goodnight, Mr. Fortune.

26:02.187 --> 26:03.772
[clears throat]

26:07.400 --> 26:10.362
[indistinct chatter]

26:10.403 --> 26:13.323
[dramatic music]

26:13.365 --> 26:20.288
♪ ♪

26:20.372 --> 26:23.708
- What are you doing here?
The building is closed today.

26:27.545 --> 26:29.464
- What happened
to Casterbridge Pacific?

26:29.506 --> 26:31.549
- I don't know what
you're talking about.

26:31.633 --> 26:33.843
- This is their office.

26:33.885 --> 26:36.888
Mr. Crowther--I met
with Crowther right in here.

26:37.847 --> 26:39.683
Who owns this place?

26:39.724 --> 26:42.560
- I don't know who rents what,
but the office is empty.

26:42.602 --> 26:44.938
- No, no, I was here last week,

26:45.021 --> 26:47.482
and I met a man named Crowther.

26:47.565 --> 26:49.693
♪ ♪

26:49.734 --> 26:51.528
Casterbridge Pacific
was the plaque on the wall.

26:51.569 --> 26:55.448
- I'm sorry, sir, but it would
appear that you are mistaken.

26:55.532 --> 26:57.617
Now I must ask you to leave.

26:57.701 --> 27:04.833
♪ ♪

27:09.087 --> 27:10.422
- Where is she?

27:10.505 --> 27:11.798
- Who?
- Miss Beaton.

27:11.881 --> 27:13.967
Maud Beaton!
I need to see her immediately.

27:14.050 --> 27:16.219
- There's no one here
by that name.

27:16.302 --> 27:17.971
- But this is where she lives.

27:18.054 --> 27:22.267
- This is the home
of Mr. and Mrs. Whitmore.

27:22.350 --> 27:23.768
- That doesn't make any sense.

27:23.852 --> 27:25.520
- Is there something wrong,
Bevan?

27:25.603 --> 27:27.439
- I must see Miss Beaton.

27:27.522 --> 27:31.109
- Who?
- Maud Beaton!

27:31.151 --> 27:33.486
I've collected her from here
and brought her home.

27:33.570 --> 27:35.864
- Only my wife and I live here.

27:37.407 --> 27:38.783
- No, that can't be true.

27:38.825 --> 27:40.618
- I'm going to send
for the police.

27:40.702 --> 27:42.287
- There's no need
to send for anyone.

27:42.370 --> 27:44.289
I'll go.

27:44.330 --> 27:49.753
♪ ♪

27:49.794 --> 27:52.297
- Are we all here?

27:52.380 --> 27:53.965
Shall we begin?

27:54.049 --> 27:56.718
- I invited Maud Beaton, but I
never heard back from her.

27:56.801 --> 27:59.304
I suppose she must
still be in Newport.

27:59.387 --> 28:03.141
- Well, I'm afraid I haven't
been much use recently.

28:03.183 --> 28:04.976
I've been very busy
helping Mrs. Roebling

28:05.060 --> 28:08.271
with her reception for
the Brooklyn Bridge opening.

28:08.313 --> 28:11.941
- How festive the decorations
are, all over the city.

28:11.983 --> 28:14.361
I suppose you're going, Bertha?
- We'll be there.

28:14.444 --> 28:16.071
It seems right to celebrate
with the Roeblings.

28:16.154 --> 28:17.822
After all, he built the bridge.

28:17.864 --> 28:20.575
- I look forward to seeing
you there, Mrs. Russell.

28:20.658 --> 28:22.660
And we must arrange
a time for you

28:22.702 --> 28:26.539
to come and inspect
your box at the Academy.

28:26.623 --> 28:28.541
- You've taken a box
at the Academy?

28:28.625 --> 28:30.001
How can that be?

28:30.085 --> 28:31.878
- I thought you were leading
the Metropolitan charge.

28:31.961 --> 28:34.839
- Happily, I was able to
secure a box for Mrs. Russell.

28:34.881 --> 28:36.925
She's waited long enough.

28:37.008 --> 28:39.719
And Carrie will be thrilled
to see you there, my dear.

28:39.803 --> 28:41.763
- I can't believe it.

28:41.846 --> 28:44.224
Have you waved the white flag
in your opera war?

28:44.307 --> 28:45.517
- No.

28:45.558 --> 28:48.812
I'm grateful to Mrs. Astor
for her kindness, of course.

28:48.853 --> 28:50.980
But I can't change horses now.

28:51.022 --> 28:53.733
My place is
at the Metropolitan.

28:55.527 --> 28:57.862
- I don't understand.

28:57.904 --> 29:00.990
Isn't a box at the Academy
what you've always wanted?

29:01.032 --> 29:02.784
- I'm sorry,
but I've thought about it,

29:02.867 --> 29:04.869
and I want
to stay loyal to the Met.

29:04.911 --> 29:06.705
- You'll regret it.

29:06.788 --> 29:09.374
In fact, I feel sorry for you,

29:09.416 --> 29:12.127
making a fool of yourself
in public like this.

29:12.210 --> 29:14.796
- It was you who decided to do
it in front of an audience.

29:14.879 --> 29:16.548
- Because I could not
have imagined you

29:16.589 --> 29:20.760
to be so deluded
as to turn me down.

29:20.844 --> 29:22.721
Good day, Mrs. Fane.
- [laughs nervously]

29:22.804 --> 29:24.347
But we haven't
started the meeting.

29:24.389 --> 29:25.932
- Well, I cannot stay.

29:26.016 --> 29:29.185
Can someone fetch my carriage?
- Of course.

29:29.227 --> 29:32.063
- Mrs. Astor,
I'd hate to embarrass you.

29:32.105 --> 29:35.066
That's the last thing
I would want to do.

29:35.108 --> 29:37.485
- Well, you have
a funny way of showing it.

29:37.569 --> 29:40.447
[soft music]

29:40.530 --> 29:46.244
♪ ♪

29:46.327 --> 29:48.872
- Oscar.

29:48.913 --> 29:51.166
- Is she here?
Maud Beaton.

29:51.249 --> 29:53.001
- I invited her,
and she never arrived.

29:53.084 --> 29:56.463
Why?
- Who is she?

29:56.546 --> 29:58.089
How did you meet her?

29:58.131 --> 29:59.924
- I can't remember exactly.

29:59.966 --> 30:02.761
She was just a part
of our group.

30:02.802 --> 30:04.971
- She's deceived all of us.

30:05.055 --> 30:07.557
She's deceived me.

30:07.599 --> 30:09.017
- There must be some mistake.

30:09.100 --> 30:11.603
- Yes, and the mistake is mine.

30:11.644 --> 30:18.276
♪ ♪

30:18.360 --> 30:22.113
- This is really thrilling.
- [sighs]

30:25.450 --> 30:27.077
[dog barking]

30:27.118 --> 30:29.329
- Oh, Marian.
Where were you?

30:29.412 --> 30:30.497
- Walking Pumpkin.

30:30.580 --> 30:32.624
- You should get one
of the servants to do that.

30:32.665 --> 30:35.126
Where were you earlier?
- I was helping Miss Scott.

30:35.168 --> 30:37.003
- [sighs]
Have you heard from Oscar?

30:37.087 --> 30:39.464
- No.
- What can be keeping him?

30:39.506 --> 30:41.299
- Well, it's practically
impossible to get a cab.

30:41.383 --> 30:43.718
The streets are so busy.
- That's no excuse.

30:43.802 --> 30:45.387
He should be
with his family now.

30:45.470 --> 30:47.013
I don't understand
either one of you.

30:47.097 --> 30:48.765
- Well, I'm here now,
Aunt Agnes.

30:48.807 --> 30:50.809
- What is going on down here?

30:50.850 --> 30:52.227
Your voices are carrying.

30:52.310 --> 30:54.479
- I was scolding Marian
for going out.

30:54.562 --> 30:56.773
- I wanted her to.

30:56.815 --> 30:59.150
There's nothing
she can do here.

30:59.234 --> 31:02.153
There's nothing any
of us can do.

31:02.237 --> 31:05.156
- How is he?

31:05.240 --> 31:08.410
- Dr. Lewis has told me
to find a clergyman.

31:09.369 --> 31:11.996
It ought to be Tim,
Luke's curate.

31:14.374 --> 31:16.459
- I'll send John.

31:20.839 --> 31:21.840
[bell rings]

31:21.923 --> 31:24.676
[loud arguing]

31:24.718 --> 31:25.885
- Gould, please.

31:25.969 --> 31:27.512
- Either you're a liar,
or you're a fool.

31:27.595 --> 31:29.472
- Gould, please.

31:29.514 --> 31:31.766
- Gentlemen.
Gentlemen!

31:31.808 --> 31:33.768
I have not given in
to the workers' demands.

31:33.852 --> 31:34.978
- You've given them a raise!

31:35.020 --> 31:36.271
- A modest raise
to the tradesmen

31:36.354 --> 31:38.023
for a short contract,
that is all.

31:38.106 --> 31:39.858
And I have not
recognized the union.

31:39.899 --> 31:41.359
- But you forced us
to follow suit.

31:41.401 --> 31:43.319
- In six months' time,
the tradesmen

31:43.361 --> 31:45.447
and the common laborers will
be at each other's throats.

31:45.530 --> 31:47.157
And we will have
the upper hand once again.

31:47.198 --> 31:49.075
- But in the meantime,
we must install

31:49.159 --> 31:52.996
absurd and expensive safety
measures in order to compete.

31:53.038 --> 31:55.165
- A reputation for safety
is good for business.

31:55.206 --> 31:56.833
We owe them that much.

31:56.916 --> 31:58.918
- But we do not owe them
a share of the profits.

31:59.002 --> 32:01.004
We're agreed on that.
- Say what you like.

32:01.046 --> 32:02.714
You failed us, Russell.

32:02.797 --> 32:04.799
We were to be united
against the union.

32:04.883 --> 32:06.217
But you've gone off
on your own.

32:06.259 --> 32:08.261
- I've done what was sensible
for my business.

32:08.345 --> 32:09.804
But I've set my own agenda.

32:09.888 --> 32:11.681
And I'd advise you
to do the same

32:11.723 --> 32:13.683
before your workers set theirs.

32:13.725 --> 32:16.019
- Well, you're on your own now.

32:16.061 --> 32:18.438
You put us against you.

32:21.566 --> 32:24.527
[indistinct chatter]

32:24.569 --> 32:25.987
- We must make a plan.

32:26.071 --> 32:29.074
- No.
First, we wait and see.

32:29.157 --> 32:30.909
- Why are you cooking
all that food?

32:30.950 --> 32:32.577
No one has any appetite.

32:32.619 --> 32:37.123
- People could be coming
by the house when he--

32:37.207 --> 32:39.167
- It's a waste, if you ask me.

32:39.250 --> 32:41.711
- No one asked you,
Miss Armstrong.

32:41.795 --> 32:44.464
I can't help
the Reverend or Miss Ada,

32:44.547 --> 32:46.132
but I can cook.

32:46.216 --> 32:48.760
- Let me take those.

32:48.843 --> 32:50.929
- Jack, take up the tea.

32:50.970 --> 32:53.139
- Yes, Mrs. Bauer.

32:57.435 --> 32:59.646
- Oscar?

32:59.729 --> 33:01.940
- Ma'am, Mr. Montgomery.

33:02.023 --> 33:04.359
- Sorry, Aunt Agnes.
It's only me.

33:04.401 --> 33:05.318
- Oh, Dashiell.

33:05.402 --> 33:08.405
At least one man
in this family heeds my call.

33:08.446 --> 33:10.990
- Where is Oscar?
You haven't heard from him?

33:11.074 --> 33:12.575
- He's been held up.

33:12.617 --> 33:14.786
I'm sure he'll come
as soon as he can.

33:14.828 --> 33:17.205
- John, you delivered the note?

33:17.288 --> 33:20.125
- I gave it to his man, but
Mr. Oscar wasn't home, ma'am.

33:20.166 --> 33:22.210
- Perhaps he's having trouble
getting about the city.

33:22.293 --> 33:24.379
People are out everywhere,
all because of the bridge.

33:24.462 --> 33:27.424
- The truth is, my son
is no good in times like these.

33:27.465 --> 33:29.801
Perhaps that's
why he stays away.

33:29.884 --> 33:31.261
Dashiell, please do sit down.

33:31.302 --> 33:33.513
Marian, get him some tea.

33:37.017 --> 33:40.145
[indistinct chatter]

33:41.146 --> 33:43.815
- Remarkable, don't you think?

33:43.857 --> 33:46.776
[dog barking]

33:50.864 --> 33:52.907
- The money's gone.

33:52.949 --> 33:54.617
They must have cashed
the check the moment

33:54.659 --> 33:57.120
I left the building.

33:57.162 --> 33:59.831
- And nobody questioned it?

33:59.914 --> 34:01.541
- They asked the manager.

34:01.624 --> 34:05.211
But since he knew my writing,
and I'd made no complaints,

34:05.295 --> 34:07.464
he let it through.

34:08.922 --> 34:10.382
- What about the police?

34:10.467 --> 34:12.427
- I'll report it,
but it could take years,

34:12.510 --> 34:15.804
and it's unlikely I could prove
a crime had been committed.

34:15.847 --> 34:17.349
They'd say
they tried their best,

34:17.389 --> 34:19.225
but the company went under.

34:22.062 --> 34:24.647
- I'm so very sorry.

34:26.733 --> 34:29.485
- The sad thing is,
I really liked her.

34:31.071 --> 34:32.739
I'm not pretending
I was in love or anything,

34:32.822 --> 34:35.033
but she was good company.

34:35.116 --> 34:37.952
She made me laugh.

34:38.036 --> 34:40.955
I really thought
we could be happy.

34:41.039 --> 34:43.166
- You mean happy enough.

34:44.542 --> 34:46.378
- [sighs]

34:46.460 --> 34:49.630
Why aren't you out making merry
with the rest of the city?

34:49.714 --> 34:51.716
I never thought
you'd be here when I came.

34:51.800 --> 34:53.717
- I didn't want to fight
with the whole of Manhattan

34:53.802 --> 34:55.804
to get a cab.

34:55.887 --> 34:58.223
And now I'm glad I stayed home.

34:58.264 --> 35:00.141
[firecrackers popping]

35:00.225 --> 35:01.601
- [breathes shakily]

35:01.685 --> 35:03.019
You're the only person
I could think of

35:03.061 --> 35:05.897
who might be on my side.

35:05.939 --> 35:08.191
- I'll always be
on your side, Oscar.

35:08.233 --> 35:09.776
You must know that by now.

35:09.859 --> 35:12.404
- [sobbing]
Oh, God, John.

35:12.445 --> 35:15.156
I've ruined everything.

35:16.950 --> 35:19.869
[soft music]

35:19.911 --> 35:27.085
♪ ♪

35:27.752 --> 35:30.755
- "In my Father's house
are many mansions.

35:30.797 --> 35:34.467
"If it were not so,
I would have told you.

35:34.551 --> 35:38.388
"I go to prepare
a place for you.

35:38.430 --> 35:43.018
And if I go and prepare
a place..."

35:43.101 --> 35:45.395
I'm sorry.

35:45.437 --> 35:48.440
♪ ♪

35:48.481 --> 35:52.569
- "If I go and prepare
a place for you,

35:52.610 --> 35:57.365
"I will come again
and receive you unto myself,

35:57.449 --> 36:00.243
that where I am..."

36:00.285 --> 36:02.912
- "There ye may be also."

36:02.954 --> 36:06.624
- [chuckles]
Cheer up, Tim.

36:06.708 --> 36:11.880
We of all people can be sure
I'm going to my reward.

36:11.963 --> 36:14.799
- And so you are.

36:14.841 --> 36:17.886
- [breathes deeply]
Hmm.

36:19.929 --> 36:22.807
[upbeat music playing]

36:22.891 --> 36:28.104
♪ ♪

36:28.146 --> 36:30.940
- Excuse me.
The president is arriving.

36:30.982 --> 36:33.193
I'll give the first speech,
and then it's you, Mr. Russell.

36:33.276 --> 36:35.362
- Thank you.

36:37.280 --> 36:39.699
- I look forward
to meeting him.

36:39.783 --> 36:43.995
♪ ♪

36:44.079 --> 36:45.622
- Mr. President.
- Thank you.

36:45.663 --> 36:48.333
- Mr. President.
- Glad to be here.

36:48.375 --> 36:50.293
- Good to have you here, sir.

36:50.335 --> 36:52.962
- Mr. President.
- Welcome, sir, this way.

36:53.046 --> 36:54.297
- Welcome to New York,
Mr. President.

36:54.339 --> 36:58.009
- Betsy, Mabel!
- I am so glad you're here.

36:58.051 --> 37:00.470
We sure have missed you.
Look at you.

37:00.553 --> 37:02.472
[laughter]

37:02.514 --> 37:05.850
- When I looked over
and saw it was Peggy Scott,

37:05.892 --> 37:07.727
well, you could've knocked me
over with a feather.

37:07.811 --> 37:09.896
- It's been too long.

37:09.979 --> 37:12.857
- We've been keeping up with
your work at the newspaper.

37:12.941 --> 37:15.110
- Thank you.
How are you both?

37:15.193 --> 37:16.778
Mabel, are you and Daniel
still together?

37:16.861 --> 37:19.155
- I'd say so,
since now they have twins.

37:19.197 --> 37:22.158
- Congratulations.
I'm so happy for you both.

37:22.200 --> 37:24.160
- Oh, we're going
to have a party next month.

37:24.202 --> 37:25.912
I hope you can join us.
- Oh, you must.

37:25.995 --> 37:27.372
- I will.

37:27.414 --> 37:28.957
And now I can come by way
of the Brooklyn Bridge.

37:29.040 --> 37:31.251
- [laughs]
- Peggy.

37:31.334 --> 37:33.545
- Excuse me,
my mother's calling.

37:38.216 --> 37:40.802
- Thank you for coming.

37:40.885 --> 37:42.220
Thank you.

37:42.262 --> 37:45.765
- Mr. President,
Mr. Roebling, Mrs. Roebling.

37:45.849 --> 37:49.436
May I present His Grace,
the Duke of Buckingham.

37:49.519 --> 37:50.729
- Pleasure to meet you,
Mr. President.

37:50.770 --> 37:52.105
- Did you know
he was in New York?

37:52.188 --> 37:53.189
- Of course not.

37:53.231 --> 37:55.025
He told me he was arriving
the day of the opening.

37:55.066 --> 37:56.401
- Yes, I'm glad to be here.

37:56.484 --> 37:58.069
- Do you think she plans
to steal him away?

37:58.153 --> 37:59.988
- Mrs. Astor won't steal him.

38:00.071 --> 38:03.450
If she wants him,
she'll buy him fair and square.

38:04.534 --> 38:06.995
- Mr. Martin studied
at the Institute too.

38:07.078 --> 38:08.580
So you have that in common.

38:08.621 --> 38:10.123
- How did you find
your time there?

38:10.206 --> 38:11.458
- Oh, I loved it.

38:11.541 --> 38:13.084
The Institute inspired me
to become a teacher.

38:13.168 --> 38:16.254
I just hope we can keep the
schools open, so I can work.

38:16.296 --> 38:18.048
- Well, we'll continue
to expose what the board

38:18.089 --> 38:19.799
is trying to do in "The Globe."

38:19.883 --> 38:21.760
I have an article on it
coming out next week.

38:21.801 --> 38:23.595
- Oh.
I look forward to reading it.

38:23.636 --> 38:24.679
- Isaiah!

38:24.763 --> 38:26.348
- [chuckles]
Oh, excuse me.

38:26.431 --> 38:28.808
I see my cousin.

38:32.103 --> 38:33.855
- He's nice-looking.

38:33.938 --> 38:35.607
[clears throat]

38:36.858 --> 38:38.068
- What is it, Mother?

38:38.109 --> 38:39.444
- I'm only going
to say this once.

38:39.486 --> 38:41.363
Don't spend all
your time writing

38:41.446 --> 38:43.573
about other folks' lives
and forget to live your own.

38:43.615 --> 38:46.076
- [laughing]
That's not what I'm doing.

38:46.117 --> 38:48.119
Can you just watch
the fireworks?

38:48.161 --> 38:49.579
It's why we're here.

38:49.621 --> 38:50.705
- Well,
you're not covering this

38:50.789 --> 38:52.415
for "The Globe" too, are you?

38:52.457 --> 38:55.752
- No, Mr. Fortune
assigned another journalist.

38:56.961 --> 38:59.964
- Like he had another
journalist in Tuskegee?

39:01.800 --> 39:04.719
That is what you told me,
isn't it?

39:04.803 --> 39:06.054
- [sighs]

39:06.137 --> 39:08.973
- Wasn't true, was it?

39:09.057 --> 39:11.101
- No.

39:12.977 --> 39:16.856
- Mr. Fortune is obviously
quite taken with you.

39:16.940 --> 39:18.274
- He respects my work.

39:18.316 --> 39:20.443
- Which I pray
is the extent of it

39:20.485 --> 39:22.362
because I raised you
better than that.

39:22.445 --> 39:24.155
- Ah, here they are.

39:24.197 --> 39:26.574
You seem very earnest.

39:26.658 --> 39:28.159
What are you talking about?

39:28.201 --> 39:30.120
- Peggy's work at "The Globe."

39:30.161 --> 39:32.080
- That's very important,
of course.

39:32.163 --> 39:35.959
But I think tonight, we
should just admire the bridge

39:36.001 --> 39:40.171
and give thanks for what man
has achieved in our lifetime.

39:40.213 --> 39:41.965
- Quite right.

39:42.007 --> 39:43.508
- I think that is right.

39:43.591 --> 39:46.678
[indistinct chatter]

39:46.720 --> 39:51.349
♪ ♪

39:51.433 --> 39:54.352
[somber music]

39:54.394 --> 39:59.190
♪ ♪

39:59.274 --> 40:01.818
- [groans]

40:01.860 --> 40:07.032
♪ ♪

40:07.115 --> 40:09.701
- Can I get you anything else?

40:12.037 --> 40:13.663
- What time is it?

40:13.705 --> 40:15.040
[coughs]

40:15.123 --> 40:17.375
- I don't know. Why?

40:17.459 --> 40:18.960
Do you have an engagement?

40:19.044 --> 40:21.921
- [laughs weakly]

40:24.215 --> 40:26.217
That's nice.

40:26.301 --> 40:28.053
- What?

40:28.094 --> 40:30.513
- To see you smile.

40:33.558 --> 40:36.644
- My darling,

40:36.728 --> 40:40.774
it's all right if you

40:40.857 --> 40:42.901
go now.

40:44.194 --> 40:46.905
I'll be fine.

40:46.946 --> 40:50.909
Being loved by you
has made me strong.

40:50.950 --> 40:53.953
- Thank you.

40:54.037 --> 40:57.457
- For what?

40:57.540 --> 41:01.002
- For loving me back.

41:01.086 --> 41:03.713
- How could I not?

41:10.011 --> 41:12.764
- And now
that our distinguished guests

41:12.847 --> 41:16.017
have declared the New York
and Brooklyn Bridge open,

41:16.101 --> 41:17.936
we can take the time
to acknowledge some

41:17.977 --> 41:20.438
of the great New Yorkers
who worked behind the scenes

41:20.480 --> 41:22.691
to create New York's
latest miracle,

41:22.774 --> 41:24.984
including our trustees,
most of whom are here tonight.

41:25.068 --> 41:29.197
Mr. Russell,
may I invite you to speak?

41:29.280 --> 41:33.952
- I am glad to be here
and to salute all of you.

41:33.993 --> 41:37.205
But my son, Larry,
will speak for me.

41:39.666 --> 41:41.626
- [clears throat]

41:43.586 --> 41:47.507
Mr. President,
gentlemen, ladies.

41:47.590 --> 41:49.676
My father asked me
to oversee our interest

41:49.759 --> 41:53.263
in the Brooklyn Bridge project,
which I was happy to do.

41:53.304 --> 41:55.598
Like most of you,
I too was in awe

41:55.640 --> 41:57.434
of the grandeur
that was once a dream

41:57.475 --> 41:59.394
and has now become a reality.

41:59.477 --> 42:03.231
I know I speak for us all
when I thank you, Mr. Roebling,

42:03.314 --> 42:05.066
for your vision.

42:07.318 --> 42:10.113
But what most
of you do not know

42:10.196 --> 42:12.282
is that after an early injury,

42:12.365 --> 42:14.159
while Mr. Roebling
was out of action,

42:14.242 --> 42:17.454
his wife, Mrs. Roebling,

42:17.495 --> 42:19.873
a brilliant engineer
in her own right,

42:19.956 --> 42:22.417
is the one who enabled
construction of the bridge

42:22.500 --> 42:24.502
to continue
in her husband's absence.

42:24.544 --> 42:27.672
[crowd murmuring]

42:27.714 --> 42:29.883
- Yes, that's right.

42:29.966 --> 42:33.762
Mrs. Roebling took over
the creation and finished it.

42:35.263 --> 42:38.433
I would like us all to raise
a glass to Emily Roebling,

42:38.475 --> 42:40.643
to thank her
for her enormous contribution

42:40.685 --> 42:43.563
to the creation
of the Brooklyn Bridge,

42:43.646 --> 42:45.607
a new wonder of the world.

42:45.690 --> 42:48.109
- Hear, hear.
all: Hear, hear!

42:48.193 --> 42:49.611
- Thank you.

42:49.694 --> 42:52.572
[upbeat music]

42:52.655 --> 42:57.869
♪ ♪

42:57.911 --> 43:00.789
- Do you have plans
this evening, Mrs. Bruce?

43:00.872 --> 43:03.083
- Plans? To do what?

43:03.166 --> 43:05.168
- Watch the fireworks.

43:05.210 --> 43:06.503
The paper said it's to be

43:06.544 --> 43:08.630
the largest
fireworks display ever.

43:08.713 --> 43:10.548
- I've only ever
seen fireworks once,

43:10.590 --> 43:13.218
and that was a long time ago.

43:13.301 --> 43:17.263
- Would you like to see
the Brooklyn Bridge fireworks?

43:17.347 --> 43:18.515
- How?

43:18.556 --> 43:21.351
- I have a plan,
if you'll join me.

43:24.229 --> 43:27.065
♪ ♪

43:27.148 --> 43:28.650
[both laugh]

43:28.733 --> 43:31.569
[indistinct chatter]

43:31.611 --> 43:38.743
♪ ♪

43:41.955 --> 43:44.666
- I hope you don't mind I made
you the center of my speech.

43:44.749 --> 43:46.543
- Not at all.

43:46.584 --> 43:48.795
I ought to thank you.

43:48.878 --> 43:50.588
- Well, at least now
you'll have

43:50.672 --> 43:52.590
the recognition you deserve.

43:52.632 --> 43:53.758
- I'm afraid these things

43:53.842 --> 43:55.969
are a little more complicated
than that.

43:56.052 --> 43:58.763
They will print
that I was a wonderful wife

43:58.805 --> 44:02.350
who served her husband
to the best of her abilities.

44:02.434 --> 44:05.937
They will ignore the true
nature of my contribution.

44:07.230 --> 44:08.732
That will be our secret.

44:08.773 --> 44:10.775
[fireworks popping]

44:10.817 --> 44:13.945
[crowd exclaiming]

44:13.987 --> 44:20.952
♪ ♪

44:31.629 --> 44:34.799
[fireworks popping]

44:34.841 --> 44:36.634
- What do you think,
Mrs. Bruce?

44:36.718 --> 44:38.553
Are you pleased
or disappointed?

44:38.636 --> 44:41.473
- Oh!
Pleased, certainly.

44:41.514 --> 44:45.977
These are the most spectacular
fireworks I've ever seen.

44:46.019 --> 44:48.605
- I thought you'd only
seen them once before.

44:48.646 --> 44:50.982
- [laughs]

44:51.024 --> 44:53.485
Well, I suppose that's true.

44:53.526 --> 44:58.281
But I can't imagine they
come much better than this.

44:58.323 --> 44:59.449
[gasps]
- Oh!

44:59.491 --> 45:06.456
♪ ♪

45:13.672 --> 45:16.049
- [chuckles]

45:19.386 --> 45:22.180
- Ah.
- It's incredible.

45:22.263 --> 45:29.187
♪ ♪

45:30.105 --> 45:32.023
- Oh, wow.

46:08.476 --> 46:11.396
- Oh.

46:11.479 --> 46:13.690
Luke.

46:13.732 --> 46:15.734
[gasps]

46:15.775 --> 46:18.153
No.

46:18.236 --> 46:19.529
Luke.

46:19.571 --> 46:21.406
No.

46:21.489 --> 46:23.408
Luke.

46:23.491 --> 46:25.827
Oh!

46:28.621 --> 46:30.331
Oh, my darling.

46:30.415 --> 46:33.335
[sobbing]

46:33.418 --> 46:36.338
[soft music]

46:36.421 --> 46:43.345
♪ ♪

46:51.269 --> 46:54.230
[sobbing]

46:57.275 --> 46:59.986
- It's all right.

47:08.870 --> 47:11.956
[indistinct chatter]

47:13.083 --> 47:16.044
- I'm making my way
to the depot shortly.

47:18.046 --> 47:20.840
- Are you sure I can't stay?

47:20.924 --> 47:22.384
- You've been kind
to keep me company.

47:22.467 --> 47:24.094
But you ought
to get back to Frances,

47:24.135 --> 47:26.179
to be there when she wakes up.

47:26.262 --> 47:28.264
- Will you be all right?
- Oh, don't worry about me.

47:28.306 --> 47:30.809
It's Aunt Ada
who needs our attention.

47:30.892 --> 47:32.936
- I'll call you tomorrow.

47:32.977 --> 47:35.146
- It is tomorrow.

47:35.230 --> 47:38.108
- Then I'll see you
later today.

47:43.780 --> 47:46.032
- Miss Brook.

47:47.200 --> 47:48.660
- How was your evening?

47:48.743 --> 47:50.328
- Well,
the fireworks were astounding.

47:50.412 --> 47:51.621
- Oh?

47:51.705 --> 47:53.248
- You must have
seen them from here.

47:54.165 --> 47:56.751
Have you been crying?

47:56.835 --> 47:58.795
- My uncle died last night.

47:58.837 --> 48:00.463
- Oh.

48:00.505 --> 48:02.674
I'm so sorry.

48:02.716 --> 48:04.926
- Thank you.

48:08.722 --> 48:10.515
It doesn't seem fair,

48:10.557 --> 48:13.601
when Aunt Ada
is such a gentle, kind soul.

48:13.685 --> 48:15.979
I mean, I wouldn't even be here
if it weren't for her.

48:16.021 --> 48:18.815
She was the one who sent
for me from Pennsylvania.

48:18.857 --> 48:21.067
- I should thank her.

48:21.151 --> 48:22.652
- Heaven knows
I never would have been able

48:22.694 --> 48:25.321
to manage Aunt Agnes
without her.

48:25.363 --> 48:27.907
- Perhaps I should
get you inside.

48:27.991 --> 48:29.909
- Oh, no.
I can't go back in there.

48:29.993 --> 48:32.203
Not just yet.
[sniffles]

48:34.372 --> 48:36.750
- Might a walk help a little?

48:36.833 --> 48:39.044
Get some air?

48:41.671 --> 48:45.300
- Thank you, Mr. Russell.
You're a good friend.

48:45.383 --> 48:51.222
♪ ♪

48:51.264 --> 48:53.475
Will you tell me
about the bridge?

48:53.558 --> 48:55.060
- It's magnificent.

48:55.101 --> 48:58.688
- Morning, Mr. Griffin.
- Hello, Jack.

48:58.730 --> 49:00.607
Here's one for you there.

49:00.690 --> 49:03.568
[upbeat music]

49:03.651 --> 49:10.575
♪ ♪

49:16.664 --> 49:20.001
- Bridget took up a tray,
but I doubt she's touched it.

49:20.043 --> 49:22.754
- I put it on the table.
I didn't know what else to do.

49:22.796 --> 49:25.757
- Poor Miss Ada.
To wake up a widow.

49:25.799 --> 49:27.384
- I just hope
she got some sleep.

49:27.425 --> 49:29.427
Mrs. Van Rhijn
never went to bed.

49:29.469 --> 49:30.929
- What can we do?

49:31.012 --> 49:33.264
- Our jobs.

49:34.683 --> 49:36.518
- Jack?

49:36.559 --> 49:38.269
What is it?
- Nothing.

49:38.353 --> 49:41.439
I'll tell you later.
- Tell us now.

49:41.523 --> 49:43.024
- I got a letter
from Mr. Bannister's friend,

49:43.108 --> 49:44.234
Mr. Schubert.

49:44.275 --> 49:45.443
- And?

49:45.527 --> 49:47.779
- He's made me a member of
his Watchmakers' Association.

49:47.821 --> 49:51.116
So now the patent office
will consider my application.

49:51.199 --> 49:53.159
- Oh, that's wonderful!

49:53.243 --> 49:54.786
- Doesn't mean
they'll approve it.

49:54.869 --> 49:56.496
- It's good news just the same.

49:56.579 --> 49:58.790
Well done, Jack.

49:58.832 --> 50:05.797
♪ ♪

50:08.299 --> 50:09.884
- Oscar.

50:09.968 --> 50:11.553
How long have you been here?

50:11.636 --> 50:12.971
- I've just arrived.

50:13.054 --> 50:15.682
- I sent word yesterday
that we needed you here.

50:15.765 --> 50:17.350
- What can I say?

50:17.434 --> 50:19.978
I'm sorry.

50:20.061 --> 50:22.147
- You look terrible.

50:22.188 --> 50:23.940
- John Adams said
much the same.

50:23.982 --> 50:27.318
- And you smell
of day-old whiskey.

50:28.862 --> 50:31.031
What is it?

50:32.073 --> 50:34.075
- Something terrible
has happened.

50:34.159 --> 50:35.869
- Yes,
your Uncle Luke has died.

50:35.952 --> 50:37.245
That is quite enough
for one day.

50:37.328 --> 50:39.372
- No, I'm afraid
this mess is of my doing.

50:39.456 --> 50:41.374
I've, um...

50:43.668 --> 50:45.086
I've made a bad mistake.

50:45.170 --> 50:47.964
- Well, you're here now,
albeit too late to help.

50:48.006 --> 50:50.258
- My mistake
involves you, Mother.

50:50.300 --> 50:51.217
- Me?

50:51.301 --> 50:52.927
- I made an investment

50:53.011 --> 50:55.472
that paid a large dividend
in a short time.

50:55.513 --> 50:59.642
So when I had the chance
to invest more, I did.

50:59.684 --> 51:01.269
A great deal more.

51:01.353 --> 51:04.606
- Does this mean you've
invested the Van Rhijn money?

51:05.815 --> 51:07.692
Well, how much?

51:08.693 --> 51:12.530
How much of my money
did you invest, Oscar?

51:12.572 --> 51:15.533
- I've just learned
that the company doesn't exist.

51:17.035 --> 51:18.370
None of it exists.

51:18.411 --> 51:19.913
Casterbridge Pacific,
Maud Beaton,

51:19.996 --> 51:21.331
the woman who led me there--

51:21.373 --> 51:23.708
- I don't understand.
She's Aurora's friend too.

51:23.792 --> 51:27.212
- She was everyone's friend,
but no one really knew her.

51:27.253 --> 51:30.382
She lied to us all.

51:30.423 --> 51:33.134
And now she's taken our money.

51:33.218 --> 51:35.679
- Well,
then you have to get it back.

51:35.720 --> 51:37.013
Go and get our money back!

51:37.055 --> 51:38.765
- I can't!

51:38.848 --> 51:40.058
There's no recourse.

51:40.141 --> 51:43.687
The money is gone,
and so is she.

51:43.728 --> 51:47.315
- How much did you lose?

51:47.399 --> 51:50.527
- Nearly all of it.

51:50.568 --> 51:52.737
- [gasps]

51:52.821 --> 51:54.906
[dramatic music]

51:54.948 --> 51:56.866
[exhales sharply]

51:56.908 --> 52:03.873
♪ ♪

53:11.775 --> 53:14.319
[bright tone]
